> return redirect(301, 'https://kit.svelte.dev');

This looks incorrect. I believe it should be `throw redirect(301, 'https://kit.svelte.dev');`

Although I suppose that doesn't matter since you'd never get there because of the `if (true)` above it. Kind of a confusingly written example...

@Conduitry The example for `server.js` seems to contradict the idea that `error()` is only for load functions?

https://kit.svelte.dev/docs/routing#server

```ts
// src/routes/api/random-number/+server.js
import { error } from '@sveltejs/kit';

export function GET({ url }) {
  const min = Number(url.searchParams.get('min') ?? '0');
  const max = Number(url.searchParams.get('max') ?? '1');
 
  const d = max - min;
 
  if (isNaN(d) || d < 0) {
    throw error(400, 'min and max must be numbers, and min must be less than max');
  }
 
  const random = min + Math.random() * d;
 
  return new Response(String(random));
}
```
